The paper deals with algorithmic frameworks and approximations for combinatorial problems, which are typically studied in computer science subfields such as data structures (cs.DS), computational complexity (cs.CC), information theory (cs.IT), graph theory (cs.GT), and machine learning (cs.LG). The use of the Sherali-Adams algorithm suggests a focus on optimization and linear programming, which is often studied in the context of computational complexity and approximation algorithms. Therefore, the most likely sub-categories are cs.DS and cs.CC, followed by cs.IT, cs.GT, and cs.LG.
